2236},{"text":4267,"type":75,"marks":7396},[7397,7399],{"type":149,"attrs":7398},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7401,"type":75,"marks":7402}," changes this equation entirely. By digitizing and automating yard operations, you can dramatically cut idle time, slash emissions, and transform your facility into a model of sustainable logistics. The technology exists today to make this shift—and the returns extend far beyond environmental compliance.",[7403],{"type":149,"attrs":7404},{"color":2236},{"type":69,"attrs":7406,"content":7407},{"level":138,"textAlign":139},[7408],{"text":7409,"type":75,"marks":7410},"Understanding Idle Time and Its Environmental Impact in Yard Operations",[7411,7413],{"type":149,"attrs":7412},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"type":112,"attrs":7415,"content":7416},{"textAlign":139},[7417,7423],{"text":7418,"type":75,"marks":7419},"Idle time",[7420,7422],{"type":149,"attrs":7421},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7424,"type":75,"marks":7425}," refers to the period when trucks and trailers are stationary in yard operations without any productive activity. This can include waiting for dock assignments, going through manual check-in processes, or being parked unnecessarily due to poor coordination. Essentially, it's the hidden productivity killer that wastes resources while vehicles keep their engines running for climate control, refrigeration, or simply because drivers don't have clear instructions on when they'll move next.",[7426],{"type":149,"attrs":7427},{"color":2236},{"type":112,"attrs":7429,"content":7430},{"textAlign":139},[7431,7436,7442],{"text":7432,"type":75,"marks":7433},"The environmental impact of this waiting game is significant. On average, a single idling truck consumes about 0.8 gallons of fuel per hour and emits approximately 20 pounds of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere. When you consider the hundreds of truck movements that occur daily at busy distribution centers, it adds up to thousands of gallons wasted each year—fuel that serves no operational purpose but directly contributes to ",[7434],{"type":149,"attrs":7435},{"color":2236},{"text":7437,"type":75,"marks":7438},"greenhouse gas emissions",[7439,7441],{"type":149,"attrs":7440},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7443,"type":75,"marks":7444},".",[7445],{"type":149,"attrs":7446},{"color":2236},{"type":69,"attrs":7448,"content":7449},{"level":1432,"textAlign":139},[7450],{"text":7451,"type":75,"marks":7452},"How Traditional Yard Management Contributes to Inefficiencies",[7453,7455],{"type":149,"attrs":7454},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"type":112,"attrs":7457,"content":7458},{"textAlign":139},[7459],{"text":7460,"type":75,"marks":7461},"Traditional yard management practices worsen these inefficiencies due to inherent structural issues:",[7462],{"type":149,"attrs":7463},{"color":2236},{"type":1340,"content":7465},[7466,7482,7498,7514],{"type":1299,"content":7467},[7468],{"type":112,"attrs":7469,"content":7470},{"textAlign":139},[7471,7477],{"text":7472,"type":75,"marks":7473},"Manual gate processes:",[7474,7476],{"type":149,"attrs":7475},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7478,"type":75,"marks":7479}," Drivers are required to exit their vehicles, complete paperwork, and wait for verbal instructions.",[7480],{"type":149,"attrs":7481},{"color":2236},{"type":1299,"content":7483},[7484],{"type":112,"attrs":7485,"content":7486},{"textAlign":139},[7487,7493],{"text":7488,"type":75,"marks":7489},"Paper-based dock scheduling:",[7490,7492],{"type":149,"attrs":7491},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7494,"type":75,"marks":7495}," This creates information gaps between yard coordinators and dock supervisors.",[7496],{"type":149,"attrs":7497},{"color":2236},{"type":1299,"content":7499},[7500],{"type":112,"attrs":7501,"content":7502},{"textAlign":139},[7503,7509],{"text":7504,"type":75,"marks":7505},"Limited visibility:",[7506,7508],{"type":149,"attrs":7507},{"color":2236},{"type":710},{"text":7510,"type":75,"marks":7511}," Yard jockeys have 